What is derived
---------------
Historically, the CTLL compile-time LL(1) parser (via the
compile-time-lark submodule) powered the type-level grammar path; it
descended from Hana Dusikova's CTRE via notre. As of 2026-07 no CTLL
code ships in this tree - the constexpr value parser is self-contained
- but the repository's git history contains CTLL, and this notice
preserves the lineage.
This repository began as a clone of its sibling compile-time-xml
(https://github.com/alexios-angel/compile-time-xml) and keeps its git
history; the build and packaging scaffolding follows the sibling
projects compile-time-json and compile-time-json5
(https://github.com/alexios-angel/). The HTML grammar, the
tree-construction layer, document types and the cthtml API are
original to this repository.

The named character reference data (include/cthtml/entities.hpp,
generated by tools/gen-entities.py) is the WHATWG HTML Standard's
named character references table
(https://html.spec.whatwg.org/multipage/named-characters.html),
obtained via CPython's html.entities module.

Attribution for the historical CTLL engine belongs to Hana Dusikova;
this file preserves it as required by Section 4(c) of the Apache
License 2.0 for the versions that shipped it.

(The former grammar layer, ctlark, and its Lark-language heritage -
Erez Shinan and the lark-parser project - left with the type path;
this tree has no submodules.)
